{"query_id": "6986f3b5-66f1-4205-a7d4-ba960eaa05d0", "timestamp": "2026-07-03T01:03:11.751106", "user_query": "What is the derivative of x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 1?", "task_type": "math", "routing_tier": "medium", "models_used": ["deepseek-v4-pro"], "strategy": "direct_specialist", "responses": {}, "final_answer": "The derivative of \\( f(x) = x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 1 \\) is found using the power rule, which states that the derivative of \\( x^n \\) is \\( n x^{n-1} \\).\n\nApplying this term by term:\n- The derivative of \\( x^3 \\) is \\( 3x^2 \\).\n- The derivative of \\( 2x^2 \\) is \\( 2 \\cdot 2x = 4x \\).\n- The derivative of \\( -5x \\) is \\( -5 \\).\n- The derivative of the constant \\( 1 \\) is \\( 0 \\).\n\nSo, the derivative is:\n\\[\nf'(x) = 3x^2 + 4x - 5\n\\]", "self_qa_score": null, "confidence": null, "latency_ms": 3399, "cost_estimate": null, "success": true, "error": null}
